🧠 Concept 1: Operators in C (How Logic Happens)
✅ What it is

Operators are symbols that perform operations on data.

int a = 10, b = 5;
int sum = a + b;
💡 Real-World Analogy

Think of operators like tools 🛠️:

+ → Add tool

- → Subtract tool

* → Multiply tool

/ → Divide tool

👉 Variables = raw materials
👉 Operators = tools to process them

⚙️ Why it works (Important 🔥)

👉 C converts expressions into machine-level instructions

Example:

int c = a + b;

Internally:
👉 CPU performs addition using registers

📚 Types of Operators (Placement Focus)
1. Arithmetic
+  -  *  /  %
2. Relational (Comparison)
>  <  ==  !=  >=  <=
3. Logical (Decision Making)
&&  ||  !
🔥 Important Trick (VERY ASKED)
Integer Division Problem
int a = 5 / 2;
printf("%d", a);  // Output: 2 ❗

👉 Why?

Because:

Both are integers → result is integer

Decimal part is removed

🔗 Connection to what you know

Same as Java/C++

But more strict than Python

👉 In Python:

5 / 2 = 2.5

👉 In C:

5 / 2 = 2
💻 Example
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int a = 10, b = 3;

    printf("%d\n", a + b); // 13
    printf("%d\n", a / b); // 3
    printf("%d\n", a % b); // 1

    return 0;
}
🧠 Memory Trick

👉 Remember:

“If both are int → result is int.”

🧠 Concept 2: Input & Output (printf & scanf)
✅ What it is

👉 How your program talks to the user

printf() → Output

scanf() → Input

💡 Real-World Analogy

Think of program like a person 🧑‍💻:

printf() → speaking

scanf() → listening

⚙️ Why it works (Important 🔥)

👉 Both come from stdio.h

👉 scanf() uses memory addresses to store input

This is VERY IMPORTANT:

int a;
scanf("%d", &a);

👉 &a means:
“Store value in address of a”

🔥 Why & is used (INTERVIEW QUESTION)

👉 Because C works with memory directly

Variable = box

& = location of that box

👉 scanf needs location, not value

🔗 Connection to what you know

In Python:

a = int(input())

👉 No need for address (handled automatically)

In C:
👉 YOU control memory → more powerful, but tricky

💻 Example
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int age;

    printf("Enter your age: ");
    scanf("%d", &age);

    printf("Your age is %d", age);

    return 0;
}
🧠 Memory Trick

👉 Remember:

“scanf needs address, printf needs value.”

